<BaseLayout
  title="LongMemEval-S Leaderboard — Engram vs Chronos, Mastra, OMEGA, Zep · JamJet Benchmarks"
  description="Engram v0.1.0 on LongMemEval-S 500q with the official judge — alongside Chronos, Mastra, OMEGA, and Zep on accuracy + license + MCP + local."
  canonical="https://jamjet.dev/benchmarks/engram-longmemeval/"
>
<Fragment slot="head">
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(compareLd)}></script>
</Fragment>

<div class="lb-wrap">
  <a class="back-link" href="/benchmarks/">← Back to JamJet benchmarks</a>

  <header class="lb-header">
    <span class="section-label">Memory · LongMemEval-S</span>
    <h1>LongMemEval-S Leaderboard</h1>
    <p class="lb-subhead">Engram v0.1.0 vs the published frontier, judged on the same methodology.</p>
    <p class="lb-intro">
      LongMemEval-S is the standard 500-question evaluation for long-form agent memory. The numbers
      below come from each system's published methodology, judged by the LongMemEval official
      gpt-4o-mini judge. Engram v0.1.0 &mdash; the open-source memory layer in
      <a href="https://github.com/jamjet-labs/engram">jamjet-labs/engram</a> &mdash; lands fifth of
      five on raw accuracy. The matrix below shows why that isn't the whole story.
    </p>
    <p class="lb-intro">
      Raw accuracy is one axis. Engram is also Apache 2.0, runs against any OpenAI-compatible model
      (including local ones), is MCP-native, and self-hosts on SQLite. Each axis is a real engineering
      decision criterion &mdash; not all of them are visible in a single accuracy number.
    </p>
    <p class="last-updated">Last updated 2026-05-09</p>
  </header>

  <section class="lb-section">
    <h2>Leaderboard</h2>
    <p class="lb-section-intro">
      All scores reported on LongMemEval-S 500-question evaluation, judged by the official
      gpt-4o-mini judge. Each row links to the system's source.
    </p>
