  <section class="lb-section">
    <h2>How to read this</h2>
    <p>
      The frontier systems above use Claude Opus 4.6 (Chronos) or GPT-5-mini (Mastra) as their reader,
      which sets a hard floor on cost and a hard ceiling on which models you can run. Engram's 64.6%
      comes from the gpt-4o-mini stack &mdash; open-source, MCP-native, runs against any
      OpenAI-compatible model (including local ones via Ollama), self-hosts on SQLite, and ships
      per-tenant isolation by default. If your constraint is &ldquo;highest raw accuracy regardless
      of cost or deployment shape,&rdquo; pick Chronos, Mastra, or OMEGA. If your constraint is
      &ldquo;the open-source memory system that runs in our VPC, doesn't lock us into a frontier
      model, ships per-tenant isolation by default, and speaks MCP today,&rdquo; Engram is the
      system on that axis. We publish our number with the official judge, the methodology, and the
      reproduction script &mdash; submit yours.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="lb-section">
    <h2>Cost footnote</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Rough cost-per-question estimates</strong> (back-of-envelope; verify against your own
      usage). Frontier-model systems running Claude Opus 4.6 or GPT-5-mini typically cost
      <strong>$0.05&ndash;$0.20 per LongMemEval-S question</strong> end-to-end. Engram's gpt-4o-mini
      stack runs <strong>~$0.005 per question</strong>. Multi-thousand-question evaluation runs with
      frontier-model stacks cost real money; budget accordingly.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="lb-section">
    <h2>Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Benchmark.</strong>{' '}
      <a href="https://github.com/xiaowu0162/LongMemEval">LongMemEval-S</a> &mdash; the standard
      500-question evaluation for long-form agent memory.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Judge.</strong> LongMemEval official gpt-4o-mini judge. Same judge as every entry above.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Engram configuration.</strong> v0.1.0 release stack: gpt-4o-mini reader,
      <strong>synthesis-mode reading</strong> for preference questions, <strong>recall-mode
      reading</strong> with verifier for everything else, query decomposition, 6-built-in-tool
      registry, two-stage retrieval, classifier-driven category budgets, today-anchored temporal
      grounding, hybrid retrieval (vector + BM25 + recency + graph + importance + temporal). Both
      reading modes documented in{' '}
      <a href="https://github.com/jamjet-labs/engram/tree/main/src/engram/read"><code>src/engram/read/</code></a>.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Reproduction:</strong></p>
    <pre class="repro"><code>{`git clone https://github.com/jamjet-labs/engram && cd engram
uv sync
export OPENAI_API_KEY=sk-...   # for the official judge + reader
export LONGMEMEVAL_ORACLE=path/to/longmemeval_oracle.json
uv run python -m benchmarks.smoke_runner --n 500 --decompose --tools`}</code></pre>
    <p class="lb-note">
      Per-question result JSON lands in <code>benchmarks/reports/</code>. Synthesis-mode is
      auto-routed by the smoke_runner's question classifier &mdash; no separate flag needed.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="lb-section">
    <h2>Per-category breakdown</h2>
    <p class="lb-section-intro">
      Where Engram v0.1.0 is competitive today, and where the roadmap work is. Honest disclosure
      &mdash; single-session and preference categories are strong; multi-session and temporal-reasoning
      are the open roadmap items.
    </p>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table class="lb-mini">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Category</th>
            <th>Score</th>
            <th>Raw</th>
            <th>Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>single-session-assistant</strong></td>
            <td><strong>95%</strong></td>
            <td>53 / 56</td>
            <td>Strongest category &mdash; synthesis-mode and recall-mode both excel here</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>single-session-user</strong></td>
            <td><strong>83%</strong></td>
            <td>58 / 70</td>
            <td>Strong</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>single-session-preference</strong></td>
            <td><strong>70%</strong></td>
            <td>21 / 30</td>
            <td>Strong &mdash; synthesis-mode reading is purpose-built for this category</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>knowledge-update</td>
            <td>65%</td>
            <td>51 / 78</td>
            <td>Roadmap &mdash; belief revision and update detection planned</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>temporal-reasoning</td>
            <td>54%</td>
            <td>72 / 133</td>
            <td>Roadmap &mdash; today-anchored grounding helps; long-span temporal chains need work</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>multi-session</td>
            <td>51%</td>
            <td>68 / 133</td>
            <td>Roadmap &mdash; largest single uplift opportunity; cross-session entity linking planned</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="lb-section-intro">
      Single-session and preference categories are where Engram's synthesis-mode reader and
      per-category routing pull their weight. Multi-session and temporal-reasoning are the open
      roadmap items &mdash; see{' '}
      <a href="https://github.com/jamjet-labs/engram#roadmap">Engram's roadmap</a> for the planned
      work.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="lb-section">
    <h2>Engram's own progression</h2>
